When a small group of creatures (one small population) are separated from the main population from which they originate (for example, if they pass through a mountain or a river, or if they pass through a new island and cannot easily return), they often find themselves in a different environment than before.
This new environment has different resources and different competitors, so the new population must have different properties or adapt to be stronger competitors than it needed before.
The original population did not change anything; they still need the same adaptations.
Over time, as the new population begins to adapt to the new environment, it will increasingly be less like the other population.
After thousands or even millions of years, the two populations will be so different that they will not be called the same species.
This process is called the formation of species which means the formation of new species.
